The cytotoxicity of alcohol with different concentrations was evaluated by MTT assay (Fig. S6A). The concentrations of 0.3%, 0.6% and 0.8% alcohol with cell viability over 85% were chosen to make the model of alcoholic fatty liver in L-02 cells. The results of Oil Red O staining indicate that there is obvious lipid droplet accumulation (red) in L-02 cells under 100μM oleic acid and different concentrations of alcohol (0.3%, 0.6%, 0.8%) treatment for 48h (Fig. S6B and C). Based on the high sensitivity and selectivity of proposed sensor, the ALP activities in L-02 cell lysates of control group and alcoholic fatty liver model groups were measured. As shown in Fig. 6
                        , the average ALP activities in a single human liver cell were calculated to be 1.89, 2.08, 2.39, 2.50U/mg protein as well as 1.92, 2.02, 2.45, 2.68U/mg protein by colorimetric and fluorometric measurements, respectively. Meanwhile, biochemistry analyzer was also employed to measure the ALP activity in four L-02 cell lysates, and the calculated values were 1.95, 2.16, 2.51 and 2.72U/mg protein. The average relative errors between two methods (colorimetry/fluorescence vs. biochemical analyzer) were 5.4% and 3.6%, respectively. The results indicate that the ALP activities in L-02 cells generally increase in accordance with the extent of alcoholic fatty liver injury, and significant differences of ALP activity are observed between control group and alcoholic fatty liver model groups, which is consistent with the reported data [54]. Furthermore, the accuracy of dual-mode sensor was performed by adding 8.0U/L ALP standard solutions, and the recoveries of known amount of ALP in L-02 cell lysates were between 93.9% and 106.5% with the RSD ranging from 1.8% to 3.1% (Table 1
                        ). These results reveal that the dual-mode sensor for ALP was reliable when applied to measure ALP activity in biological samples.
